this! No! Not today. You guys have caused enough
problems. We are not going to push this creature

03:34:21.520 --> 03:34:27.888
on other people. I'm trying, all right? I'm
working on it. I don't want to push this problem

03:34:27.888 --> 03:34:34.210
off on a town that's already being held hostage by
vampires. That fucking sucks! That's double

03:34:34.210 --> 03:34:35.568
shitting on them.

03:34:35.568 --> 03:34:41.369
ORION: Well, the other option was, like I was
saying, perhaps you can form an agreement with

03:34:41.369 --> 03:34:48.477
Emon. I'm sure it would pay in livestock rather
well for the protection of you, such a powerful

03:34:48.477 --> 03:34:53.478
druid, over at least a section of the land. In
exchange for free food for your friend.

03:34:53.478 --> 03:35:08.824
MATT: "You, dragon man, are adorably naive of the
ways of men and those that lie and deceive. I have

03:35:08.824 --> 03:35:19.446
"yet to have met any civilized people who have kept
their word when it came to creatures like this."

03:35:19.446 --> 03:35:28.932
LAURA: Can I come forward? All right. What about
Vasselheim? Not in the city, but outside of it.

03:35:28.932 --> 03:35:32.278
There's plentiful forests, tons of giant creatures
it could feed on.

03:35:32.278 --> 03:35:34.648
ORION: That's right! That's true!

03:35:34.648 --> 03:35:36.466
MARISHA: That actually is fairly true.

03:35:36.466 --> 03:35:42.304
LAURA: There's so many monsters out there, they
don't hunt them all because there's too many.

03:35:42.304 --> 03:35:45.899
ORION: That's a wonderful idea, Vex. Yes!

03:35:45.899 --> 03:35:49.027
MATT: Make a persuasion check.

03:35:49.027 --> 03:35:51.358
ORION: I'll aid her, as well.

03:35:51.358 --> 03:35:57.855
MATT: I'll say you've aided one person recently.
This'll just be her check on this. He really

03:35:57.855 --> 03:35:59.574
doesn't trust you, given the current
circumstances.

03:35:59.574 --> 03:36:01.992
LAURA: 21.

03:36:01.992 --> 03:36:03.748
MATT: Natural 20.

03:36:03.748 --> 03:36:17.755
LAURA: Then as a natural 20, you know that's good
for you. That's the best place you can go. You can

03:36:17.755 --> 03:36:20.489
see the wisdom in my persuasion.

03:36:20.489 --> 03:36:24.297
ORION: It is true, though. I mean, it's just feed
walking all around for it.

03:36:24.297 --> 03:36:28.523
MARISHA: Please, please listen to us. We're only
trying to help.

03:36:28.523 --> 03:36:34.987
SAM: Is there a young creature around here besides
the--

03:36:34.987 --> 03:36:37.681
MATT: No, looking about you, no.

03:36:37.681 --> 03:36:40.020
SAM: There's no babies there?

03:36:40.020 --> 03:36:43.291
MATT: No. This is the young. This bird is like the
adolescent.

03:36:43.291 --> 03:36:48.054
MARISHA: Please believe me. I let this thing
almost take my hand off, and I'm still standing

03:36:48.054 --> 03:36:55.339
here fairly cogently talking to you, so please
take that as a sign of honesty.

03:36:55.339 --> 03:37:00.664
LAURA: I go and put my hand on her back and cast
Cure Wounds, because I got that spell now, yo!

03:37:00.664 --> 03:37:05.307
SAM: Where are we telling them to go?

03:37:05.307 --> 03:37:06.701
TRAVIS: To Vasselheim.

03:37:06.701 --> 03:37:07.999
SAM: Vasselheim?

03:37:07.999 --> 03:37:14.942
MARISHA: Listen. She's right. We have friends in
Vasselheim. We can contact the Slayer's Take.

03:37:14.942 --> 03:37:21.327
We're a part of their guild. We can tell them that
you're coming. They'll not bother you. We can tell

03:37:21.327 --> 03:37:25.454
them they are not allowed to take out a contract
on your creature. You will not be harmed.

03:37:25.454 --> 03:37:28.178
LAURA: Don't bring up contracts, Keyleth. Maybe
just don't even bring it up.

03:37:28.178 --> 03:37:33.076
MARISHA: Because they don't have mercenaries out
there. It has to be approved! So it's really

03:37:33.076 --> 03:37:34.155
good.

03:37:34.155 --> 03:37:40.016
MATT: "And what's to stop them from hunting down a
majestic creature as rare as this one?"

03:37:40.016 --> 03:37:42.221
ORION: Us!

03:37:42.221 --> 03:37:43.822
MATT: "You, who live here in Emon?"

03:37:43.822 --> 03:37:46.333
ORION: Yes. No, us who are members of the guild.

03:37:46.333 --> 03:37:50.732
MATT: "So you also are monster slayers, who come
here under the guise to slay this monster?"

03:37:50.732 --> 03:37:54.641
ORION: No! Not here. Other places that we're
forced to do it. But still we're members.

03:37:54.641 --> 03:37:57.204
MATT: "It's too much talk."

03:37:57.204 --> 03:38:01.917
TRAVIS: Can we kill this thing now? You guys are
doing awesome.

03:38:01.917 --> 03:38:10.431
MARISHA: I feel like I've done pretty damn good!
Come on, man!

03:38:10.431 --> 03:38:19.967
SAM: I start speaking in Gnome to him. Listen.
Earlier, you said that this place was perfect. It

03:38:19.967 --> 03:38:24.982
was safe. There were no large predators. Well,
you're looking at six large predators. We'll keep

03:38:24.982 --> 03:38:29.882
hunting you down and hunting your beast down until
you get out of here. This is your one and only

03:38:29.882 --> 03:38:35.255
warning. You must leave, and you must leave now.
We're giving you a good choice, a safe choice. We

03:38:35.255 --> 03:38:41.344
can help you get there and be safe there. But if
you don't listen to us, we'll start killing.

03:38:41.344 --> 03:38:45.433
MATT: Make a persuasion roll.

03:38:45.433 --> 03:38:48.348
MARISHA: How many fucking persuasion rolls does
this asshole need?

03:38:48.348 --> 03:38:51.447
SAM: Persuasion?

03:38:51.447 --> 03:38:58.258
MATT: This is essentially a conversational skill
challenge. So every success and failure leads

03:38:58.258 --> 03:39:00.518
towards where the conversation's going to end.

03:39:00.518 --> 03:39:02.270
SAM: 32.

03:39:02.270 --> 03:39:13.316
MATT: He gives you a look. Very intense, looking
into your very essence-type stare. His little

03:39:13.316 --> 03:39:28.606
beady gnomish eyes meeting yours. (sighs) "If
we're going to make this journey to where you say

03:39:28.606 --> 03:39:31.259
"this Vasselheim is, how far is it?"

03:39:31.259 --> 03:39:33.106
SAM: Several days' journey.

03:39:33.106 --> 03:39:36.093
LAURA: It's just across the water. You could fly
no problem over it.

03:39:36.093 --> 03:39:37.571
MATT: "Across the sea?"

03:39:37.571 --> 03:39:43.115
TRAVIS: It's across the sea.

03:39:43.115 --> 03:39:49.644
SAM: We can draw you a map. We can give you
provisions. We'll even make sure the farmers

03:39:49.644 --> 03:39:58.604
provide you with a few pieces of livestock to chow
down on before the journey. A parting gift to fuel

03:39:58.604 --> 03:40:07.110
up before the big ride. We can give you papers to
hand to the Slayer's Take that will ensure that

03:40:07.110 --> 03:40:09.119
you'll be treated fairly.

03:40:09.119 --> 03:40:14.707
ORION: I'll take out my Scroll of Telescription
and start writing a note.

03:40:14.707 --> 03:40:21.868
MATT: He looks back towards Keyleth, looks back at
Scanlan, looks back at Keyleth, looks up at the

03:40:21.868 --> 03:40:23.052
bird.

03:40:23.052 --> 03:40:28.164
MARISHA: Please. We really don't need another
death on our conscience today.

03:40:28.164 --> 03:40:41.099
MATT: "Then looks like we don't have much of a
choice, do we? If you can assure us enough food to

03:40:41.099 --> 03:40:49.774
"get across on this journey, we'll make our way
towards this Vasselheim. I pray on the solidarity

03:40:49.774 --> 03:40:58.954
"between our kin, and our kin, that you speak the
truth that resonates this moment. Because if it

03:40:58.954 --> 03:41:03.967
"does not, may the fall of this entity and myself
weigh on your conscience."

03:41:03.967 --> 03:41:09.015
ORION: I flip over the note that I'm writing to
him and then I trigger it (flying noise) as he's

03:41:09.015 --> 03:41:10.419
reading it.

03:41:10.419 --> 03:41:24.103
MATT: All right. It (poof) vanishes. "As the sun
rises, two sizable pieces of livestock to be

03:41:24.103 --> 03:41:31.160
"placed at the boundaries of the usual hunting
site. If those are there, and it is taken without

03:41:31.160 --> 03:41:39.004
"any sort of aggression, we'll take that as a sign
that you are being honest, and we shan't bother

03:41:39.004 --> 03:41:41.098
"you or your people any further."

03:41:41.098 --> 03:41:44.939
SAM: I bow deeply and when I do, it goes (cowbell
ringing).

03:41:44.939 --> 03:41:55.426
MATT: For a moment, you think you hear a slight,
uncontrollable chuckle from the gnome.

03:41:55.426 --> 03:42:05.786
ORION: As that's going on, because we're going to
head back right now to seal this up, right? Then

03:42:05.786 --> 03:42:13.292
I'll do my Teleportation Circle. Which is closer
to the northeast: the Lyceum or the Keep?

03:42:13.292 --> 03:42:17.493
MATT: To the north side of it? That would be the
Lyceum.

03:42:17.493 --> 03:42:20.304
LAURA: We could fly back pretty fast. Couldn't
we?

03:42:20.304 --> 03:42:22.295
MATT: If he has another Fly spell, you could take
it right back.

03:42:22.295 --> 03:42:24.002
LAURA: Yeah, we can just fly back.

03:42:24.002 --> 03:42:30.492
MARISHA: Before he leaves. Well, wait! We've got
to go to the farm.

03:42:30.492 --> 03:42:33.953
SAM: We've got to go to the farmers. We've got to
buy some cows off them.

03:42:33.953 --> 03:42:42.857
MARISHA: And I tell him, if you're up that way,
there's a druidic tribe, a little village called

03:42:42.857 --> 03:42:51.542
Pyrah. They're Fire Ashari. You can find their
headmaster Cerkonos. He's a friend. You might find

03:42:51.542 --> 03:42:55.234
your people there. Who knows? Maybe friends will
do you good.

03:42:55.234 --> 03:43:02.734
MATT: "Ashari, you say? My dealings with them have
been mixed. Perhaps I'll keep my distance."

03:43:02.734 --> 03:43:10.288
LAURA: Can I see if there's any feathers dropped
from the giant bird creature?

03:43:10.288 --> 03:43:12.017
MATT: There are ample around.

03:43:12.017 --> 03:43:13.989
LAURA: Can I grab a few of them?

03:43:13.989 --> 03:43:17.526
MATT: As you go and reach up, slaps you across the
knuckles.

03:43:17.526 --> 03:43:20.950
LAURA: Can I have a feather that he dropped?

03:43:20.950 --> 03:43:22.367
MATT: "Why?"

03:43:22.367 --> 03:43:27.637
LAURA: Because they're beautiful. You have to
admit they're beautiful.

03:43:27.637 --> 03:43:33.965
MATT: (sighs) "Elves. All right."

03:43:33.965 --> 03:43:35.601
LAURA: Thank you.

03:43:35.601 --> 03:43:39.841
MATT: You take three roc feathers.

03:43:39.841 --> 03:43:42.432
TRAVIS: They're huge, right?

03:43:42.432 --> 03:43:45.554
MATT: Yeah. They're almost boat size.

03:43:45.554 --> 03:43:48.064
ORION: I put one in my Bag of Holding, too.

03:43:48.064 --> 03:43:57.260
MATT: You guys manage to get one for you and three
for you guys before he's like, "Now go! Now! My

03:43:57.260 --> 03:44:03.622
"patience wears thin. I'm through with talking
words." (sighs)

03:44:03.622 --> 03:44:05.220
SAM: Sorry.

03:44:05.220 --> 03:44:07.922
LIAM: I walk out from behind him and just walk past.

03:44:07.922 --> 03:44:09.801
MATT: (yelps)

03:44:09.801 --> 03:44:12.151
SAM: (laughs) Sorry about that.

03:44:12.151 --> 03:44:15.759
ORION: All right. I'll burn another 5th-level and
then fly us all out.

03:44:15.759 --> 03:44:28.593
MATT: Okay. You guys coast back to the north side
of Emon. You go to the door where the Klaus family

03:44:28.593 --> 03:44:35.387
is, and you speak with them for a while. You
manage to convince them of the situation and what

03:44:35.387 --> 03:44:40.120
seems to be a mutually positive circumstance. They
agree it's better to lose two cows than continue

03:44:40.120 --> 03:44:41.205
this.

03:44:41.205 --> 03:44:43.593
LAURA: I pay them for their two cows. Being nice,
man!

03:44:43.593 --> 03:44:45.167
MATT: How much do you give them?

03:44:45.167 --> 03:44:48.839
LAURA: How much are cows usually worth?

03:44:48.839 --> 03:44:50.636
MATT: You've never purchased a cow, so you don't
know.

03:44:50.636 --> 03:44:53.056
LAURA: Yes I have! I purchased Dork the ox.

03:44:53.056 --> 03:44:54.738
MATT: An ox is not a cow.

03:44:54.738 --> 03:44:58.607
LAURA: Shit! How much do your cows normally cost,
darling?

03:44:58.607 --> 03:45:05.913
MATT: This is a good question. Let me look in the book.
I've not had to look up the cost of a cow before.

03:45:05.913 --> 03:45:26.572
I would put it at about maybe 40 gold each.

03:45:26.572 --> 03:45:29.083
LAURA: That's way more than I expected.

03:45:29.083 --> 03:45:33.606
MATT: Because they can be used for meat, they can
be used for milk.

03:45:33.606 --> 03:45:41.019
LAURA: 40 gold each to make up for the loss of
your cows.

03:45:41.019 --> 03:45:45.048
MATT: "Thank you so much. I greatly appreciate you
helping with this. And you promise, this will--"

03:45:45.048 --> 03:45:48.183
SAM: Yes, just put them out in the open field.

03:45:48.183 --> 03:45:49.225
TRAVIS: We'll take them.

03:45:49.225 --> 03:45:50.392
SAM: Oh, we'll take them?

03:45:50.392 --> 03:45:52.245
TRAVIS: We'll put them out there. Stake them.

03:45:52.245 --> 03:45:53.711
SAM: Okay, we'll take care of it.

03:45:53.711 --> 03:45:57.883
MATT: You guys take two of the cows. You bring
them to the outskirts. With rope tied around their

03:45:57.883 --> 03:46:05.281
neck, you essentially hitching-post them to the
outside of this open area, about 20 to 30 feet

03:46:05.281 --> 03:46:12.182
from the actual holding pen. A few hours go by,
and the sun slowly begins to rise.

03:46:12.182 --> 03:46:14.660
LAURA: Along with some other food, right?

03:46:14.660 --> 03:46:20.630
MATT: Place some of their feed and things around
there. Eventually, the sun begins to rise across

03:46:20.630 --> 03:46:27.182
the eastern sky. As it crests, you can see some of
the farmers come out, anxiously watching from

03:46:27.182 --> 03:46:35.879
their homes. You see different families gathering.
The wings beating in the air, and it swoops down

03:46:35.879 --> 03:46:40.866
(swoosh) and grabs two of them. You can see some
of the families gasp and rush inside, and some are

03:46:40.866 --> 03:46:47.700
amazed to see this even happen. It takes the two,
carries them up, and heads out over the Ozmit Sea,

03:46:47.700 --> 03:46:53.805
passing to the northwest side, and over the next
30 or so minutes, slowly disappears over the

03:46:53.805 --> 03:46:55.950
horizon until it's no longer visible.

03:46:55.950 --> 03:46:59.388
TRAVIS: The sun rose, right? Can I make a beard
check?

03:46:59.388 --> 03:47:01.207
(laughter)

03:47:01.207 --> 03:47:02.766
MATT: You may.

03:47:02.766 --> 03:47:04.707
TRAVIS: Two, zero.

03:47:04.707 --> 03:47:08.978
MATT: With that, (creak) the beginnings of the
other side of your beard slowly begins to set in.

03:47:08.978 --> 03:47:10.922
TRAVIS: What happens to the existing side?

03:47:10.922 --> 03:47:15.762
MATT: The existing side has rounded itself off to
a nice beard. It's pretty much where it's going to

03:47:15.762 --> 03:47:22.712
be on that side. The other side is now starting to
finally catch up. And that's where we'll end: on a

03:47:22.712 --> 03:47:25.089
successful beard check.

03:47:25.089 --> 03:47:30.433
SAM: Wow. That was a crazy night.

03:47:30.433 --> 03:47:37.151
TRAVIS: Perspiration was happening.

03:47:37.151 --> 03:47:38.886
MARISHA: Yeah, it was.

03:47:38.886 --> 03:47:40.791
SAM: I gave you my hand.

03:47:40.791 --> 03:47:44.691
MATT: More battle maps that will never get used.

03:47:44.691 --> 03:47:49.233
LAURA: Look at us not fighting things. That's
really beautiful.

03:47:49.233 --> 03:47:52.164
MATT: That would have been really bad, too.

03:47:52.164 --> 03:47:54.484
LAURA: I'm glad we didn't fight it.

03:47:54.484 --> 03:47:56.064
TRAVIS: Bad for us?

03:47:56.064 --> 03:47:58.917
MATT: Well, just imagine a giant bird that grabs
you and then drops you off the side of a mountain.

03:47:58.917 --> 03:48:10.223
Would have been an interesting fight. Cool. That
concludes a unique Percy-less bottle episode of

03:48:10.223 --> 03:48:11.397
Critical Role.

03:48:11.397 --> 03:48:13.267
TRAVIS: Squadron of cows.

03:48:13.267 --> 03:48:18.719
MATT: Squadron of flying midnight cows. That is
probably the weirdest thing that's ever-- no,

03:48:18.719 --> 03:48:22.931
there's been weirder. That's in the top five of
weird things that's happened in DND for me.

03:48:22.931 --> 03:48:24.598
SAM: Fighting "formootion."

03:48:24.598 --> 03:48:27.735
(groaning)

03:48:27.735 --> 04:41:17.460
[end of transcript]

